descriptor.long_desc: Taj Mahal attracts millions of visitors from around the world each year. Discover the enchanting allure of the Taj Mahal in Agra, a destination that promises a journey through history, culture, and unparalleled beauty. Whether you're a history buff, a culture enthusiast, or simply seeking a breathtaking experience, the Taj Mahal offers something for every traveler. An epitome of love and architectural brilliance, the Taj Mahal stands majestically on the right bank of the Yamuna River in Agra, captivating millions with its timeless beauty and intricate craftsmanship.
descriptor.name: Taj Mahal
descriptor.short_desc: The Taj Mahal in Agra, Uttar Pradesh, India, is an architectural marvel and a symbol of eternal love

additional_desc.url:

descriptor.long_desc: The success of NGMA as a cultural hub has led to the establishment of regional centres in Mumbai and Bengaluru. Here the emphasis is on artistic innovation and promoting excellence in the field of art and curatorial practices. Indigenous art and culture is given special focus as it is believed to be vital in reshaping the cultural landscape of the nation.
descriptor.name: National Gallery of Modern Art
descriptor.short_desc: The National Gallery of Modern Art is India’s premier art institution for modern and contemporary Indian art. The museum was established in 1954 with the singular aim of promoting and preserving modern Indian art. Its vast collection chronicles the trajectory of art in India from mid-18th century.

additional_desc.url:
• NGMA is spread over eight acres of prime space in the heart of New Delhi at the prestigious Indiacol
  • Collection is showcased in Jaipur House, the former palace of the Maharaja of Jaipur
  • Regal ambience of the heritage structure offers a befitting backdrop for the masterpieces on display

descriptor.long_desc:
The Pradhanmantri Sangrahalaya is a tribute to every Prime Minister of India since Independence, and a narrative record of how each one has contributed to the development of our nation over the last 75 years. It is a history of collective effort, and powerful evidence of the creative success of India’s democracy. Our Prime Ministers came from every class and tier of society, for the gates of democracy were equally open to all. Each one left an important footprint on the journey of development, social harmony and economic empowerment that has enabled India to give true meaning to freedom. We inherited an impoverished land from the debris of British colonialism, and together gave it a new life, lifting our country from famished deprivation to food-surplus status, and creating infrastructure over barren territory for the benefit of the people.
The Sangrahalaya is a seamless blend which begins at the renovated and refurbished Nehru Museum building, now completely updated and technologically advanced displays on the life and contribution of Shri Jawaharlal Nehru. The new panorama includes a section which exhibits a large number of rare gifts received by him from all over the world but never put on display.

The saga of modern India starts with the freedom struggle and the making of a great Constitution. The Sangrahalaya goes on to tell the story of how our Prime Ministers navigated the nation through various challenges and ensured the all-round progress of the country. Within this story is a message for the younger generation: there are greater horizons to conquer as we transform India into New India.

descriptor.long_desc:
Morning boat ride at the dawn followed by old city walk and  Vishwnath Corridor: Boating in the Ganges during the sunrise in Varanasi is the main attraction. Here We can observe the Hindu’s way of life on the bank of the river Ganges (Ganga Ghats).

Sarnath: Sarnath in Varanasi, is the place where Buddha chose to deliver his first sermon. It makes Sarnath one of the most venerated Buddhist places. Besides Buddhism, Sarnath is also connected with Jainism.

Evening Aarti: Aarti, also spelled arathi, is a Hindu ritual, in which light is offered to one or more deities. Aartis also refer to the songs sung in praise of the deity, when offering of lamps is being offered.
descriptor.name: Varanasi Day Tour
descriptor.short_desc: Varanasi Insight tour is based on one day or two days tours. This tour is designed for the regular tourist who comes to Varanasi for one or two day but wants to experience to way of life in India.

additional_desc.url:
• Begins 30 minutes before sunrise and ends after evening Aarti.
  • There will be two breaks in this tour, one for the breakfast after morning boat ride and old city wa
  • This tour can also be completed from 1st day afternoon to 2nd day afternoon.

descriptor.long_desc: The ancient ruins and monuments in Sarnath are a testament to its rich history and the influence of Buddhism in the region. Overall, a visit to Sarnath is a transformative experience that allows you to connect with the teachings of Lord Buddha and gain a deeper understanding of Buddhism. The positive vibes and serene atmosphere make it a perfect destination for spiritual seekers and those interested in exploring the rich history of this ancient religion.
descriptor.name: 3 Hour Walking Tour of Buddhism in Sarnath
descriptor.short_desc: Sarnath is a small town located near Varanasi in Uttar Pradesh, India. It holds immense significance for Buddhists as it is the place where Lord Buddha gave his first sermon after attaining enlightenment

additional_desc.url:
• Visiting Sarnath allows you to step back in time and experience the profound impact of Lord Buddha's
  • The atmosphere is filled with a sense of tranquility and spirituality
  • ideal place for meditation and introspection

descriptor.long_desc:
The jyotirlinga is an ancient axis mundi symbol representing the supremely formless (nirguna) reality at the core of creation, out of which the form (saguna) of Shiva appears. The jyothirlinga shrines are thus places where Shiva appeared as a fiery column of light.

There are twelve 'self manifested' jyotirlinga sites that take the name of the presiding deity; each is considered a different manifestation of Shiva. At all these sites, the primary image is a lingam representing the beginningless and endless Stambha pillar, symbolising the infinite nature of Shiva.
descriptor.name: Shri Kashi Vishwanath Temple
descriptor.short_desc: Kashi Vishwanath Temple is a Hindu temple dedicated to Shiva. It is located in Vishwanath Gali, in Varanasi, Uttar Pradesh, India. The temple is a Hindu pilgrimage site and is one of the twelve Jyotirlinga shrines.

additional_desc.url:
• The presiding deity is known by the names Vishwanath and Vishweshwara
  • The original temple, called the Adi Vishveshwar Temple, was demolished by Mohammad of Ghor
  • redevelopment of the temple complex was completed, and the Kashi Vishwanath Dham Corridor
